    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-10-08T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-10-08T02:00:00-05:00" n="982"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d982">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.111/508: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Second Secretary of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Paxton</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-10-08T16:00:00+09:00"
                            >October 8, 1941—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received October 9—11:13 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>70. It is reported that officials of Governments which have recognized the Wang
                        régime<note n="69" xml:id="d982fn1">Japanese-sponsored “government” at
                        Nanking.</note> are soon to receive passes indefinitely valid for travel
                    anywhere in Japanese occupied territory. Baggage inspection is to be waived for
                    them.</p>
                <p>Travel passes are to be issued to non-official nationals of these countries
                    indefinitely valid for specified areas permitting transportation of any articles
                    not prohibited in the case of Japanese subjects.</p>
                <p>No change in the treatment accorded Americans or nationals of other
                    non-recognizing Governments as regards travel in this area has been reported or
                    seems to be in contemplation as yet.</p>
                <p>Sent to the Department, repeated to Chungking, Peiping and Shanghai, by mail to
                    Tokyo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Paxton</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
